---
import PageLayout from '../layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '../components/Breadcrumb.astro';
import '../styles/global.css';

const siteUrl = 'https://aicostplanner.com';
const currentDate = new Date().toISOString().split('T')[0];
const route = '/openai-api-usage/';
const lastReviewed = 'June 14, 2026';

const breadcrumbs = [{ label: 'OpenAI API Usage', href: route }];
const internalLinks = [
  { href: '/openai-api-credits/', label: 'OpenAI API Credits' },
  { href: '/openai-api-billing/', label: 'OpenAI API Billing' },
  { href: '/api-billing-mismatch/', label: 'API Billing Mismatch' },
  { href: '/small-prepaid-test/', label: 'Small Prepaid Test' },
  { href: '/agent-token-usage/', label: 'Agent Token Usage' },
  { href: '/billing-transparency/', label: 'Billing Transparency' },
  { href: '/image-generation-api-cost/', label: 'Image Generation API Cost' },
];
---

<PageLayout
  title="OpenAI API Usage Guide"
  description="Learn how to read OpenAI API usage, export Activity or Cost data, use organization Usage APIs and reconcile tokens with spend."
  canonical={`${siteUrl}${route}`}
  type="article"
  lastUpdated={currentDate}
>
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
      "@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "OpenAI API Usage Guide",
      "description": "Learn how to read OpenAI API usage, export Activity or Cost data, use organization Usage APIs and reconcile tokens with spend.",
      "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "AICostPlanner" },
      "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "AICostPlanner", "url": siteUrl },
      "datePublished": currentDate, "dateModified": currentDate,
      "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": `${siteUrl}${route}` }
    })} />
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
      "@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
      "itemListElement": [
        { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": siteUrl },
        { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "OpenAI API Usage", "item": `${siteUrl}${route}` }
      ]
    })} />
  </Fragment>

  <Header />
  <main>
    <section class="hero-dark">
      <div class="container">
        <Breadcrumb items={breadcrumbs} />
        <h1 class="page-title">OpenAI API Usage Explained</h1>
        <p class="page-meta"><span class="label-mono">Last reviewed: {lastReviewed}</span></p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-light content-section">
      <div class="container container-narrow">

        <div class="quick-answer">
          <h2>Quick Answer</h2>
          <p>
            OpenAI API usage can be reviewed in the organization Usage Dashboard or retrieved through
            organization Usage APIs. The dashboard uses UTC and supports project and time filters.
            Export Activity data when investigating usage patterns and Cost data when reconciling spend.
            For financial reporting, use the Costs endpoint or Cost export rather than assuming token
            usage alone equals the final billed amount.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2>OpenAI API Usage vs Billing vs Credits</h2>
        <p>
          OpenAI's API Platform separates usage monitoring, billing administration and credit management:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Usage</strong> — how much was consumed (tokens, requests, images, audio, and so on), tracked via the Usage Dashboard and Usage APIs</li>
          <li><strong>Billing</strong> — payment arrangements, invoices, Tax ID, project budgets and payment methods; see the <a href="/openai-api-billing/">OpenAI API Billing</a> guide</li>
          <li><strong>Credits</strong> — prepaid credit balance, credit purchases, auto recharge and expiry; see the <a href="/openai-api-credits/">OpenAI API Credits</a> guide</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Who Can View the Usage Dashboard</h2>
        <p>
          OpenAI's usage documentation indicates that access to the Usage Dashboard is controlled at
          the organization level. Only Organization Owners or users explicitly granted Usage Dashboard
          permission can access it.
        </p>
        <p>
          If the Usage Dashboard is not visible, check:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>The current organization is correct (top-right selector)</li>
          <li>The account role is Organization Owner or has Usage Dashboard permission</li>
          <li>The project filter in the Usage page itself is not restricting the view</li>
          <li>The browser is logged into the correct account</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Ordinary project members and API key holders do not automatically have Usage Dashboard access.
        </p>

        <h2>Dashboard Time Zone and Date Ranges</h2>
        <p>
          OpenAI's usage documentation describes the following for the Usage Dashboard:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>The Usage Dashboard uses UTC for all time ranges</li>
          <li>Time comparisons must be normalized to UTC to avoid boundary mismatches</li>
          <li>The date-range selector applies to the currently selected project and filter set</li>
          <li>The project selector within the Usage page is independent of the top-right organization/project selector — clearing it shows the organization-level aggregate</li>
          <li>The Usage Dashboard does not automatically combine or consolidate usage across multiple organizations</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Always confirm the UTC range when reconciling usage against local logs, invoices or support requests.
        </p>

        <h2>Organization and Project Filters</h2>
        <p>
          OpenAI's API Platform project documentation describes how project filters work in the Usage Dashboard:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>The organization selector (top right) controls which organization's data is shown</li>
          <li>The project filter within the Usage page filters to a specific project; clearing it shows all projects in the selected organization</li>
          <li>These two selectors operate independently — a project selected in the Usage page does not change the top-right organization selector</li>
          <li>Changing the top-right organization clears any project selection within the Usage page</li>
          <li>Usage data is scoped to a single organization and does not span organizations automatically</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Activity Data vs Cost Data</h2>
        <p>
          The Usage Dashboard provides two distinct export types:
        </p>
        <h3>Activity data</h3>
        <p>
          Activity exports provide granular usage data that can be filtered and analyzed by relevant
          dimensions such as:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Project</li>
          <li>User</li>
          <li>API key</li>
          <li>Model</li>
          <li>Batch</li>
          <li>Service tier</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Activity data is suited for investigating usage patterns, debugging cost anomalies and
          understanding request-level behavior. The Activity export is not a per-request-ID
          statement of account; it provides aggregated records.
        </p>
        <h3>Cost data</h3>
        <p>
          Cost exports provide spend data grouped by line item. Cost data is the preferred source
          for:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Monthly spend reporting</li>
          <li>Invoice reconciliation</li>
          <li>Project-level cost comparison</li>
          <li>Calendar-month financial reporting</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          For financial purposes, OpenAI recommends using the Costs endpoint or the Costs tab in the
          Usage Dashboard. Token counts alone do not always equal the final billed amount.
        </p>

        <h2>Exporting Usage and Cost CSV Files</h2>
        <p>
          OpenAI's export documentation describes the following steps:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Navigate to the Usage Dashboard in the API Platform</li>
          <li>Select the target organization and project (or leave project blank for organization-level data)</li>
          <li>Choose the calendar-month or custom UTC date range</li>
          <li>Select the Activity tab or Cost tab depending on the analysis goal</li>
          <li>Download the CSV and note the export timestamp</li>
          <li>For partial-month data, export month-to-date and compare carefully with the full-month export</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Usage API vs Costs Endpoint</h2>
        <p>
          OpenAI provides two distinct API surfaces for organization-level usage and cost data:
        </p>
        <h3>Organization Usage endpoints</h3>
        <p>
          Organization Usage APIs provide aggregated usage quantities broken down by API capability.
          These endpoints return usage for specific capabilities such as completions, embeddings, images,
          audio transcriptions, audio speech, moderations, vector stores, code interpreter sessions,
          file search calls and web search calls.
        </p>
        <p>
          Each endpoint returns data in its natural unit — tokens, images, seconds, characters, bytes,
          sessions or request counts — depending on the capability. Do not assume all endpoints
          return data in the same unit.
        </p>
        <h3>Costs endpoint</h3>
        <p>
          The <code>GET /v1/organization/costs</code> endpoint returns spend data. It may include:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><code>amount.value</code> and <code>amount.currency</code></li>
          <li><code>line_item</code></li>
          <li><code>project_id</code></li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Usage data may not always reconcile perfectly with Costs because usage and spend are
          recorded differently. For financial purposes, OpenAI recommends using the Costs endpoint
          or the Costs tab.
        </p>
        <p>
          Note: the model response <code>usage</code> object does not contain a monetary
          <code>cost</code> field. Cost must be reconstructed from token counts and applicable pricing.
        </p>

        <h2>Admin API Key Requirements</h2>
        <p>
          The organization Usage and Costs endpoints are part of the Administration API. They require
          an Admin API key, not an ordinary application API key.
        </p>
        <p>
          Key points:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>An Admin API key is separate from API keys used for model requests</li>
          <li>An Admin API key cannot be used for model inference endpoints</li>
          <li>An ordinary application API key does not grant access to organization administration endpoints</li>
          <li>Admin API keys should be read from environment variables, never hardcoded in application logic or pasted into support tickets</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Example request showing the correct endpoint and the expected key format:
        </p>
        <pre><code>curl "https://api.openai.com/v1/organization/costs?start_time=&lt;unix-seconds&gt;" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer &lt;OPENAI_ADMIN_KEY&gt;"</code></pre>

        <h2>Text and Completion Usage</h2>
        <p>
          For text and completion models, usage is measured in tokens. A single model response
          <code>usage</code> object may include:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><code>input_tokens</code> — tokens consumed by the prompt and context</li>
          <li><code>output_tokens</code> — tokens generated in the response</li>
          <li><code>total_tokens</code> — sum of input and output tokens</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          These fields are returned per request in the model response and are also aggregated by the
          organization Usage API.
        </p>

        <h2>Cached and Reasoning Tokens</h2>
        <p>
          Some models and endpoints expose additional token breakdowns. These may include:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Cached token counts and details — some requests benefit from context caching, which may affect pricing</li>
          <li>Reasoning token details — depending on the model and endpoint, reasoning tokens may be billed as output tokens even when they are not exposed as visible answer text</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Inspect the response usage fields and current model pricing documentation to determine
          how cached and reasoning tokens affect the final cost. Not all models return identical
          reasoning-token fields.
        </p>

        <h2>Image, Audio and Tool Usage</h2>
        <p>
          Different API capabilities use different billing units. Examples include:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Image generation</strong> — may be counted per image, per size, per quality tier or per source</li>
          <li><strong>Audio transcription</strong> — typically measured in seconds of audio processed</li>
          <li><strong>Audio speech</strong> — typically measured in characters of input text</li>
          <li><strong>Vector stores</strong> — typically measured in bytes stored</li>
          <li><strong>Code interpreter sessions</strong> — typically measured in session counts</li>
          <li><strong>File search / web search</strong> — typically measured in calls or requests</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Do not treat all usage as tokens. Use the relevant Usage API endpoint for each capability
          and the Costs endpoint for financial totals.
        </p>

        <h2>Grouping by Project, User, API Key and Model</h2>
        <p>
          Completions and other Usage endpoints support <code>group_by</code> parameters that
          break down usage by relevant fields such as:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><code>project_id</code></li>
          <li><code>user_id</code></li>
          <li><code>api_key_id</code></li>
          <li><code>model</code></li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Different Usage endpoints support different <code>group_by</code> values. Check the
          current API reference for the specific endpoint to confirm which grouping options are
          available.
        </p>

        <h2>Pagination and Time Buckets</h2>
        <p>
          Organization Usage API responses may be paginated. If a response includes a
          <code>next_page</code> token, use it to retrieve subsequent pages until all records
          are collected. An incomplete pagination results in under-reported totals.
        </p>
        <p>
          For time-series data, Usage endpoints support a <code>bucket_width</code> parameter that
          controls the granularity of time bucketing. Supported values depend on the endpoint.
          For the completions usage endpoint, current supported values include <code>1m</code>,
          <code>1h</code> and <code>1d</code>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Time parameters use Unix timestamps in seconds:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><code>start_time</code> is inclusive</li>
          <li><code>end_time</code> is exclusive</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Example completions usage request:
        </p>
        <pre><code>curl "https://api.openai.com/v1/organization/usage/completions?start_time=&lt;unix-seconds&gt;&bucket_width=1d" \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer &lt;OPENAI_ADMIN_KEY&gt;"</code></pre>

        <h2>Why Usage May Not Equal Final Cost</h2>
        <p>
          Token usage and billed cost are related but not always identical. Common reasons for
          a discrepancy include:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Cached tokens — context caching may result in lower effective cost than raw token counts suggest</li>
          <li>Reasoning tokens — some models bill reasoning tokens as output tokens even if they are not visible in the response text</li>
          <li>Batch vs. standard pricing — batch-mode usage may have different rates than standard on-demand usage</li>
          <li>Invoice adjustments — Enterprise contract pricing, credits and refunds may appear on an invoice but not in a list-price token estimate</li>
          <li>Time boundary mismatch — local logs and the Usage Dashboard may use different UTC ranges, causing apparent differences at month boundaries</li>
          <li>Project or organization filter mismatch — different filter settings produce different totals</li>
          <li>Automatic retries — retries may generate additional usage not reflected in application-level logs</li>
          <li>Incomplete pagination — <code>next_page</code> tokens not followed result in partial totals</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Worked Usage Reconciliation Example</h2>
        <p>
          A common reconciliation scenario:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Usage Dashboard:</strong> 12,400 model requests, 8.2M input tokens, 1.4M output tokens</li>
          <li><strong>Local application logs:</strong> 12,365 request records</li>
          <li><strong>Difference:</strong> 35 requests not accounted for in local logs</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Investigation steps:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Check for automatic retries in the application — retries may not appear in all log pipelines</li>
          <li>Verify the UTC time range matches between the dashboard export and local log query</li>
          <li>Confirm the project filter in the dashboard matches the application scope</li>
          <li>Verify pagination was completed for the API export</li>
          <li>Check whether the missing requests were batch or service-tier calls that use different API paths</li>
          <li>Confirm the correct organization is selected</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          The 35-request difference does not necessarily mean they were overcharged — it means
          the two records were not compared on the same basis.
        </p>

        <h2>Usage Reconciliation Checklist</h2>
        <ul class="checklist">
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Confirm the correct organization and Usage Dashboard permission</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Clear or select the intended project filter within the Usage page</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Normalize the time range to UTC — confirm both dashboard and local query use the same UTC boundaries</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Use inclusive start_time and exclusive end_time for API queries</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Export Activity data for usage investigation</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Export Cost data for spend reconciliation</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Match models, projects and API key IDs between records</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Compare response-level usage with organization-level aggregates</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Follow all <code>next_page</code> tokens to complete pagination</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Separate usage units by capability (tokens vs images vs seconds vs sessions)</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Use Costs endpoint or Cost export rather than token estimates for financial totals</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Compare with the <a href="/api-billing-mismatch/">API Billing Mismatch</a> guide when totals still differ</span></li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Security Checklist</h2>
        <ul class="checklist">
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Store Admin API keys in environment variables, never in source code</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Never paste API keys into browser tools, chat interfaces or support tickets</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Redact keys from screenshots before sharing evidence with support</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Rotate Admin API keys regularly and immediately upon suspected exposure</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Apply the principle of least privilege — grant Usage Dashboard access only to users who need it</span></li>
          <li><span class="checklist-icon">&#10003;</span><span>Save request_id, timestamp, model, project, local status, input/output usage and retry count for every request at the application level</span></li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Official Sources Reviewed</h2>
        <p class="official-sources">
          The information on this page is based on OpenAI's official documentation reviewed as
          of {lastReviewed}. OpenAI's API usage features may change; always verify current
          behavior in the API Platform and API reference.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>OpenAI Help: Understanding your API usage</li>
          <li>OpenAI Help: How do I export monthly usage details from the API Usage Dashboard</li>
          <li>OpenAI API Reference: Organization Usage — Costs endpoint</li>
          <li>OpenAI API Reference: Administration overview</li>
          <li>OpenAI Cookbook: Completions usage API examples</li>
          <li>OpenAI API Docs: Pricing</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Related Guides</h2>
        <div class="link-cards">
          {internalLinks.map(link => (
            <a href={link.href} class="link-card"><h4>{link.label}</h4><p>Learn more about this topic</p></a>
          ))}
        </div>

        <div class="ai-summary-block">
          <div class="ai-summary-label"><svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><path d="M12 16v-4M12 8h.01"/></svg> AI Summary</div>
          <p>
            The OpenAI Usage Dashboard and organization Usage APIs provide aggregated usage data scoped
            to a single organization and time range, using UTC. Only Organization Owners or explicitly
            authorized users can access the dashboard. Activity exports support granular breakdowns by
            project, user, API key, model and service tier. Cost exports and the Costs endpoint are
            the preferred source for financial reconciliation. Admin API keys — distinct from application
            keys — are required for organization administration endpoints. Token usage alone does not
            equal final billed cost; use the Costs endpoint for financial totals. Apply inclusive
            start_time and exclusive end_time when querying APIs, follow all next_page tokens for complete
            results, and always normalize to UTC when comparing records. AICostPlanner is an independent
            educational cost-planning site and is not affiliated with OpenAI.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Who can view the OpenAI API Usage Dashboard?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Only Organization Owners or users explicitly granted Usage Dashboard permission can access it. Ordinary project members and API key holders do not automatically have access. If the dashboard is not visible, verify the current organization, account role, permission grant, project filter and browser login.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What timezone does the OpenAI Usage Dashboard use?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">The Usage Dashboard uses UTC for all time ranges and filters. When comparing usage data against local logs, invoices or support tickets, always normalize to UTC to avoid boundary mismatches at month boundaries.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Does the Dashboard show all projects automatically?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">No. The project selector within the Usage page is independent of the top-right organization/project selector. If no project is selected in the Usage page, the view shows all projects in the selected organization. Changing the top-right organization clears any project selection within the Usage page. The Usage Dashboard does not consolidate data across multiple organizations.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What is the difference between Activity and Cost exports?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Activity exports provide granular usage data filterable by project, user, API key, model, batch or service tier — useful for investigating usage patterns. Cost exports provide spend data grouped by line item — the preferred source for spend reporting, invoice reconciliation and calendar-month financial totals.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Does the Usage API return final billed cost?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">No. The organization Usage endpoints return usage quantities (tokens, images, seconds, and so on), not monetary amounts. Use the Costs endpoint or the Costs tab in the Usage Dashboard for financial totals. Usage and spend may not reconcile perfectly due to cached tokens, reasoning tokens, batch pricing, invoice adjustments and other factors.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Do I need an Admin API key for organization usage data?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Yes. The organization Usage and Costs endpoints are part of the Administration API and require an Admin API key. An ordinary application API key used for model requests does not grant access to administration endpoints. Admin keys must not be used for model inference or pasted into support tickets.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Why does local token usage differ from the Costs endpoint?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Differences can arise from cached tokens, reasoning tokens, batch vs. standard pricing, invoice adjustments, UTC boundary mismatches, project or organization filter mismatches, automatic retries not in local logs, and incomplete pagination. For financial reconciliation, use the Costs endpoint rather than token estimates.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Can the Dashboard combine multiple organizations?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">No. Usage data is scoped to a single organization. The Usage Dashboard does not automatically combine or consolidate data across multiple organizations. You must select one organization at a time and apply the appropriate filters.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="cta-block">
          <h3>Estimate before you scale</h3>
          <p>Use a small prepaid test to measure real API cost before committing a larger budget.</p>
          <div class="cta-buttons">
            <a href="https://app.rutaapi.com/register?lng=en" class="btn btn-primary" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Create API Key</a>
            <a href="https://app.rutaapi.com/pricing" class="btn btn-secondary-dark" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View Live Pricing</a>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</PageLayout>

<style>
  .hero-dark { background: var(--color-bg-dark); padding: var(--space-12) 0 var(--space-10); border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-bg-dark-border); }
  .hero-dark :global(.breadcrumb) { margin-bottom: var(--space-6); }
  .page-title { font-size: 2.25rem; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-dark); line-height: 1.15; margin: 0 0 var(--space-4) 0; letter-spacing: -0.02em; }
  .page-meta { margin: 0; }
  .content-section { padding: var(--space-12) 0 var(--space-16); background: var(--color-bg-light); }
  .quick-answer { background: var(--color-bg-light-elevated); border-left: 4px solid var(--color-accent-blue); padding: var(--space-6); border-radius: 0 var(--radius-md) var(--radius-md) 0; margin-bottom: var(--space-10); }
  .quick-answer h2 { font-size: 1.125rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text-light); margin-bottom: var(--space-3); }
  .quick-answer p { margin: 0; color: var(--color-text-light); line-height: 1.7; }
  h2 { font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text-light); margin: var(--space-10) 0 var(--space-4); padding-top: var(--space-6); border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border-light); }
  h2:first-of-type { margin-top: 0; padding-top: 0; border-top: none; }
  h3 { font-size: 1.125rem; font-weight: 600; color: var(--color-text-light); margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-3); }
  p { color: var(--color-text-light-muted); line-height: 1.75; margin-bottom: var(--space-4); }
